1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,180
 - Hello and welcome to our lecture on owned rows in Django.

2
00:00:04,180 --> 00:00:07,180
 So what do I mean by an owned row?

3
00:00:07,180 --> 00:00:11,200
 Well up to now, every CRUD application that you've written,

4
00:00:11,200 --> 00:00:15,640
 you got a table or a model or two, maybe they're connected,

5
00:00:15,640 --> 00:00:18,920
 but basically if you log in, you can edit every row.

6
00:00:18,920 --> 00:00:21,360
 And so if you do a list, you see an update

7
00:00:21,360 --> 00:00:23,660
 and delete button on every row.

8
00:00:23,660 --> 00:00:25,520
 Real applications don't work that way.

9
00:00:25,520 --> 00:00:28,320
 If you're building a classified ad system,

10
00:00:28,320 --> 00:00:31,360
 some ads belong to you and some ads belong to other people,

11
00:00:31,360 --> 00:00:33,560
 you can see them all, but you can't edit them all.

12
00:00:33,560 --> 00:00:36,280
 And so we have to decide when to put the edit

13
00:00:36,280 --> 00:00:40,280
 and delete buttons up and only do those for the owner.

14
00:00:40,280 --> 00:00:42,040
 And we gotta make it so you can't like sneak in

15
00:00:42,040 --> 00:00:43,520
 and edit and delete other people's stuff.

16
00:00:43,520 --> 00:00:46,040
 And so we have to protect these rows

17
00:00:46,040 --> 00:00:48,760
 from being edited or deleted by anybody but the owner,

18
00:00:48,760 --> 00:00:50,560
 but anybody can see them.

19
00:00:50,560 --> 00:00:52,640
 And so that's why I call them owned rows.

20
00:00:52,640 --> 00:00:55,120
 If there's a row that you own,

21
00:00:55,120 --> 00:00:57,800
 you will see an edit or delete button.

22
00:00:57,800 --> 00:00:58,960
 If there's a row you don't own,

23
00:00:58,960 --> 00:01:00,520
 you'll see the row and the data

24
00:01:00,520 --> 00:01:03,560
 and you'll be able to read it and view it and that's it.

25
00:01:03,560 --> 00:01:07,200
 And so if we go back to how we were working

26
00:01:07,200 --> 00:01:10,640
 in our CRUD application, we were making heavy uses

27
00:01:10,640 --> 00:01:13,480
 of these generic views, the generic list view.

28
00:01:13,480 --> 00:01:16,120
 And so when we're all said and done

29
00:01:16,120 --> 00:01:20,120
 after a whole bunch of machinations,

30
00:01:20,120 --> 00:01:23,120
 you ended up with a very, very simple view.

31
00:01:23,120 --> 00:01:25,460
 You ended up with a horse list view

32
00:01:25,460 --> 00:01:27,200
 that extended generic list view.

33
00:01:27,200 --> 00:01:31,200
 Generic list view is provided to us by Django.

34
00:01:31,200 --> 00:01:34,720
 And the only thing we had to do was take this code,

35
00:01:34,720 --> 00:01:37,040
 which is several thousand lines of code,

36
00:01:37,040 --> 00:01:40,160
 and inform it as to which model we want it to be

37
00:01:40,160 --> 00:01:41,760
 and then we make another view, right?

38
00:01:41,760 --> 00:01:44,240
 So we make the horse list view

39
00:01:44,240 --> 00:01:46,280
 by extending generic list view

40
00:01:46,280 --> 00:01:49,280
 and informing that list view

41
00:01:49,280 --> 00:01:51,840
 that we wanna do this in the model with horses.

42
00:01:51,840 --> 00:01:56,840
 And from that point on, all kinds of convention happens.

43
00:01:56,840 --> 00:01:58,280
 And so we know things like

44
00:01:58,280 --> 00:01:59,980
 the variable will be named horse list.

45
00:01:59,980 --> 00:02:03,160
 It'll be a list of objects that are retrieved from,

46
00:02:03,160 --> 00:02:07,280
 a list of model objects that are retrieved from the database.

47
00:02:07,280 --> 00:02:09,920
 And so we kinda know how that works.

48
00:02:09,920 --> 00:02:14,240
 And it makes things really simple, not a lot of repetition.

49
00:02:14,240 --> 00:02:16,000
 Every view kinda looks the same.

50
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:19,400
 You probably have done cats or dogs or autos,

51
00:02:19,400 --> 00:02:20,840
 a couple of different things.

52
00:02:20,840 --> 00:02:23,840
 And they all look very much the same

53
00:02:23,840 --> 00:02:25,200
 and if you get good at it,

54
00:02:25,200 --> 00:02:28,600
 you should be able to make these changes very rapidly.

55
00:02:28,600 --> 00:02:30,220
 So if we look at how this is working

56
00:02:30,220 --> 00:02:33,160
 kinda from an object oriented perspective,

57
00:02:33,160 --> 00:02:38,160
 we are making a new class called gView.Views.HorseListView

58
00:02:38,160 --> 00:02:43,120
 and we are extending our parent class

59
00:02:43,120 --> 00:02:44,800
 is the generic list view

60
00:02:44,800 --> 00:02:48,700
 and we're sort of adding our own little special sauce

61
00:02:48,700 --> 00:02:53,280
 by saying one class variable, model equals horse.

62
00:02:53,280 --> 00:02:55,860
 Okay, so that's kinda what's going on here.

63
00:02:55,860 --> 00:03:00,700
 Now, in this owner view,

64
00:03:00,700 --> 00:03:03,240
 we're going to do something quite similar.

65
00:03:03,240 --> 00:03:05,660
 And that is when we're going to have an article

66
00:03:05,660 --> 00:03:10,440
 and this is all from the DJ Free Samples My Arts example,

67
00:03:10,440 --> 00:03:13,360
 we're going to extend owner list view.

68
00:03:13,360 --> 00:03:16,440
 Now if we were, and soon we will look inside owner list view

69
00:03:16,440 --> 00:03:17,880
 and we will see that owner list view

70
00:03:17,880 --> 00:03:21,400
 is extending generic list view

71
00:03:21,400 --> 00:03:26,400
 and where this model equals article

72
00:03:26,400 --> 00:03:28,880
 is informing owner list view,

73
00:03:28,880 --> 00:03:31,240
 the difference is this is our code.

74
00:03:31,240 --> 00:03:33,700
 That belongs to us and in the last part,

75
00:03:33,700 --> 00:03:35,920
 we will show you everything that you have to do

76
00:03:35,920 --> 00:03:37,160
 to build one of these things.

77
00:03:37,160 --> 00:03:39,120
 And so we're taking the list view

78
00:03:39,120 --> 00:03:41,480
 which has almost everything we want

79
00:03:41,480 --> 00:03:43,520
 and we're gonna add one feature to it

80
00:03:43,520 --> 00:03:45,180
 and then we're gonna extend the list view

81
00:03:45,180 --> 00:03:48,120
 and create a new view called owner list view

82
00:03:48,120 --> 00:03:51,560
 or you might call it list view for owned rows.

83
00:03:51,560 --> 00:03:55,680
 And at that point, you're good

84
00:03:55,680 --> 00:03:58,400
 and this has this class owner list view

85
00:03:58,400 --> 00:03:59,700
 which we'll see in a second,

86
00:03:59,700 --> 00:04:03,800
 has everything you need to deal with rows that are owned.

87
00:04:03,800 --> 00:04:08,800
 And for example, we're going to have a owner column.

88
00:04:08,800 --> 00:04:11,600
 So every article is gonna have an owner

89
00:04:11,600 --> 00:04:13,960
 and if that's equal to the current logged in user,

90
00:04:13,960 --> 00:04:17,760
 then we're going to show these little edit and delete buttons.

91
00:04:17,760 --> 00:04:19,240
 But if the article owner,

92
00:04:19,240 --> 00:04:23,720
 the owner value inside the article object or the model,

93
00:04:23,720 --> 00:04:26,760
 if that owner is not equal to the current user,

94
00:04:26,760 --> 00:04:27,820
 we don't show it.

95
00:04:27,820 --> 00:04:30,240
 Now, not showing a link does not mean

96
00:04:30,240 --> 00:04:31,600
 you've protected it from editing.

97
00:04:31,600 --> 00:04:35,720
 We'll show you later how that protection from editing happens.

98
00:04:35,720 --> 00:04:38,080
 But this is such a common problem

99
00:04:38,080 --> 00:04:40,340
 that we wanna just be able to, in a sense,

100
00:04:40,340 --> 00:04:42,340
 say look, here's a list view.

101
00:04:42,340 --> 00:04:44,740
 Here's a list view with this special owner column in it

102
00:04:44,740 --> 00:04:46,880
 and we wanna maintain the owner column.

103
00:04:46,880 --> 00:04:49,500
 We don't wanna have to write hundreds of lines of code

104
00:04:49,500 --> 00:04:52,160
 in every view that we wanna have this owner column.

105
00:04:52,160 --> 00:04:55,760
 So we just use object-oriented techniques to accomplish this.

106
00:04:55,760 --> 00:04:57,720
 And so we're going to use inheritance

107
00:04:57,720 --> 00:05:00,560
 and we talked about it and we'll talk about it again.

108
00:05:00,560 --> 00:05:03,680
 Inheritance is the idea that you have a class,

109
00:05:03,680 --> 00:05:06,680
 you're gonna make another class that inherits all of its,

110
00:05:06,680 --> 00:05:09,000
 all that parent class and then extends it,

111
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:11,180
 adds a little bit of stuff to it.

112
00:05:11,180 --> 00:05:13,760
 And it's another form of don't repeat yourself.

113
00:05:13,760 --> 00:05:17,020
 Do something once in a parent class.

114
00:05:17,020 --> 00:05:20,260
 You make the parent class sometimes quite generic.

115
00:05:20,260 --> 00:05:22,840
 Then you make a child class that extends the parent class

116
00:05:22,840 --> 00:05:24,520
 and then we use the child class.

117
00:05:24,520 --> 00:05:28,060
 Or we could call them subclasses or child classes.

118
00:05:28,060 --> 00:05:29,720
 There's a whole bunch of different terminology

119
00:05:29,720 --> 00:05:31,240
 and it's all pretty much equivalent.

120
00:05:31,240 --> 00:05:34,360
 Subclasses are more specialized versions of a class.

121
00:05:34,360 --> 00:05:36,480
 They inherit attributes and methods

122
00:05:36,480 --> 00:05:39,680
 from their parent classes and can introduce their own.

123
00:05:39,680 --> 00:05:43,800
 Again, basic object-oriented programming.

124
00:05:43,800 --> 00:05:45,760
 So up next we're gonna talk a little bit

125
00:05:45,760 --> 00:05:47,840
 about how it is that we can peek in

126
00:05:47,840 --> 00:05:49,760
 to one of these generic views

127
00:05:49,760 --> 00:05:52,140
 and add our own special sauce for it.

128
00:05:52,140 --> 00:05:54,560
 (jazz music)

